To save a record in Google Cloud Datastore using Node.js, you can use the `@google-cloud/datastore` library. If you haven't installed it yet, you can do so using:

```bash
npm install @google-cloud/datastore
```

Here's a basic example of how to save a record in Google Cloud Datastore using this library:

```javascript
const { Datastore } = require('@google-cloud/datastore');

// Create a new Datastore client
const datastore = new Datastore();

// Define the kind (similar to a table in relational databases)
const kind = 'Person';

// Create a new entity with a unique key (name in this case)
const entityKey = datastore.key([kind, 'john_doe']);
const entity = {
  key: entityKey,
  data: {
    first_name: 'John',
    last_name: 'Doe',
    age: 30,
  },
};

// Save the entity to Datastore
datastore
  .save(entity)
  .then(() => {
    console.log(`Saved record with key: ${entityKey.path.join('/')}`);
  })
  .catch((err) => {
    console.error('Error saving record:', err);
  });
```

In this example, the `entity` is created, properties are added to it, and then it is saved to Datastore using the `save()` method of the client. The `entityKey.path` will contain the automatically generated key for the saved entity.

Make sure you have your Google Cloud credentials set up correctly, either by setting the `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS` environment variable or through other authentication methods, to authenticate your application with Google Cloud services.

Remember to replace `'your-project-id'` with your actual Google Cloud project ID when creating the `Datastore` client.

